export const batch131 = {
  'eat-right-4-your-type.json': {
    base: { id: 'eat-right-4-your-type', title: 'Eat Right for Your Type. Complete Blood Type Encyclopedia. The A-Z Reference Guide for the Blood Type Connection to Symptoms, Disease, Conditions, Vitamins, Supplements, Herbs and Food', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781649836650 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Why your blood matters in more ways than one',
        text: "You might think blood is just blood. It moves through your veins, the heart pushes it along, and it feeds your cells and organs. Of course, blood is important. Without it, you would not survive. But have you ever thought about how your blood might shape your health, or about the different types that exist?\n\nMany people feel squeamish around blood. A single drop turns them pale. Still, blood is nothing to fear. It is a substance that supports life, helps us live longer, and offers scientists a window into the human past.\n\nBlood types reveal more about human history than almost any other scientific clue. In this case, blood is far more than just blood.\n\nBlood keeps us alive, and blood types can teach us how to feel better day to day.\n\nIn this summary, Dr. Peter D'Adamo suggests that certain foods may suit certain blood groups better than others. He also notes that the food you eat reacts with your blood. When the two clash, your body cannot pull the full nutrition from the meal.\n\nYou may not know your blood type today, but after reading this content you will likely want to find out. Once you do, you can shape your habits around it and feel your best, getting the most out of every bite for your overall health.\n\nThis summary will walk you through the main blood types, how each reacts with food, and what those reactions tell us about human history. By the end, you will see that blood is far more than red liquid moving through your body. You will understand its real meaning, and you may even grow curious about this vital substance."
      },
      {
        title: 'How blood and certain substances have fascinated people for centuries',
        text: "It all started with the discovery of blood transfusions, which gave results ranging from miraculous to disastrous.\n\nIn 1888, a researcher named Herman Stillmark decided to stop using animals in his experiments. He switched to cell cultures, and soon noticed something. When he mixed red blood cells with extracts from castor seeds, the cells clumped together. Scientists call this agglutination.\n\nHe went on to find more substances that caused this clumping and helped push the field of immunology forward.\n\nThe first big discoveries about blood happened in 1888, almost by accident.\n\nBuilding on the earlier work of German bacteriologist Pat Erlich, Dr. Karl Landsteiner identified the ABO blood group antigens and antibodies. He earned a Nobel Prize in 1930 for this work. He saw that red blood cells from some people clumped while others did not, and from this he worked out the A, B, AB, and O groups.\n\nThen, in 1945, William Clouser Boyd, Ph.D., made another fascinating find. He showed that some agglutinins only worked on specific blood groups, clumping one type while leaving others alone. The agglutinin in lima beans, for example, only clumped type A cells and did nothing to the rest.\n\nFinding blood groups became easier once scientists had the right chemicals to work with.\n\nAnthropologists began to use these tools and ideas to learn more about our shared past. Most knowledge of early humans came from written records, but to go back further, before writing existed, scientists had to look at other clues.\n\nTime wears objects down, especially our bodies, so we have lost a great deal of information about the past. It is as if the story of our species is a book with only a few pages filled in.\n\nHowever, science and decades of careful work have given us a useful tool to read what came before.\n\nA regular, intense exercise routine lifts the spirit and helps type Os stay at a healthy weight, keep their emotions steady, and build strong self-esteem, in the words of Dr. Peter J. D'Adamo."
      },
      {
        title: 'Biological markers like blood groups reveal deep truths about our past',
        text: "Each blood type handles food in its own way and reacts differently to outside threats such as parasites. Different types also come with different levels of risk, which helps explain why blood types are spread the way they are today. You could almost call it a map for reading the past.\n\nBlood reacts differently with local bacteria depending on the group.\n\nAlmost every major infectious disease that spread before antibiotics had a preference for one ABO group over the others.\n\nMany microbes have their own versions of ABO blood types. This can cause trouble. For example, a bacterium with a surface antigen that looks like the A antigen would slip into a person with type A blood more easily.\n\nEach blood type has had its moment in history, when conditions favored it. Type O rose as humans climbed to the top of the food chain. Type A spread as hunters and gatherers settled into farming communities. Types B and AB appeared later, as people moved and mixed across regions.\n\nIn the 1960s, the author's father, James D'Adamo, N.D., was the first to put forward the idea that ABO blood groups could point to the best diet for each person.\n\nHe saw that most of his patients did well on a low-fat vegetarian diet, yet a small group did not improve or even got worse. He wanted to know why, and he spent his life looking for the answer.\n\nAfter years of watching patients, a pattern appeared. Those with type A blood thrived on vegetarian meals, while those with type O felt their best on animal foods, especially meat. James D'Adamo put his findings into a book called One Man's Food. Inspired by his father's work, Dr. Peter D'Adamo spent twenty years digging deeper, focusing on blood groups, specific diets, and how they shape digestion and immunity.\n\nWe can match a diet to each blood group."
      },
      {
        title: 'Chemical analysis shows that the O antigen is the simplest of the blood groups',
        text: "Many studies over the years have looked at blood groups. Several suggested that humans were all type O for most of our history. The high rate of type O in old and isolated populations points to how ancient this group really is.\n\nMany theories of human evolution link the growth of the brain to a shift toward meat-rich eating. As humans got smarter, they became better hunters, and big game offered plenty of protein-rich meat. As we evolved, we got better at bringing down prey rich in protein, thanks to our growing intelligence.\n\nIn this stage, humans had a meat-heavy diet, and the digestive traits of type O were a perfect match. Strong stomach acid and pepsin made meat easy to break down.\n\nLarge game in Africa started to thin out, and that pushed early human ancestors to move in search of food. As they spread, they carried type O blood with them.\n\nHumans are prone to certain illnesses simply because of their blood groups.\n\nEvery blood group has its strengths, its weak spots, and conditions where it does well or poorly.\n\nThe main drawbacks of type O include a higher risk of inflammatory diseases, which often hit older people. The type O stomach handles meat well, but it tends toward ulcers because of the strong hydrochloric acid in it. Type O also has a higher rate of thyroid disease and hyperthyroidism than other ABO groups.\n\nThe strengths of type O include a low rate of gallstones, jaundice, and liver cirrhosis. It also sees less influenza and very low rates of gum disease.\n\nDr. Peter D'Adamo says that some foods are harmful for certain blood groups and very helpful for others.\n\nHere are some examples of useful diets for type O. Beneficial foods include beef, buffalo, lamb, liver, mutton, veal, venison, and bass. Neutral foods include duck egg, black bean, lima bean, soybean, tofu, hazelnut, and sesame seed. Harmful foods include cheese, ice cream, milk, yogurt, whey, peanut and peanut butter, corn, beer, coffee, and liquor.\n\nOne useful note: Dr. Peter D'Adamo points out that about one in five patients admitted to the hospital will need blood."
      },
      {
        title: 'Civilization and the growth of cities go hand in hand with the rise of blood group A',
        text: "Big game grew scarce, and people learned to farm grains and raise livestock. This shift pulled humans away from their wandering lifestyle and pushed them toward a more settled one.\n\nA species that had once moved freely now had to adjust to life in organized communities. Cities sprang up, and people lived close together for the first time. The big change in diet led to a new mutation in the digestive and immune systems. Carriers of blood group A began to appear because the new conditions favored them.\n\nA small change in what you eat can have a large effect on how you feel.\n\nOver time, humans lost some of their ability to handle the meat-heavy diet of the pre-agricultural era.\n\nAs Dr. Peter J. D'Adamo notes, the blood group A variant helped people digest grains and other farm products more easily.\n\nPeople with blood group A are also more resistant to infections common in crowded areas.\n\nAs people moved from a meat-heavy diet to one based on farming, their stomachs produced less acid. They did not need strong acid to digest vegetables, grains, and farm-raised animals, so they had fewer ulcers. In older age, type A people often see their stomach acid drop further, which can lead to digestive issues.\n\nHepatitis and common tropical liver infections that cause scarring show up more often in type A than in any other group. Pseudomonas aeruginosa, the germ behind swimmer's ear, also has a preference for type A blood. Childhood ear infections follow a similar pattern.\n\nHere are some beneficial and harmful foods for type A. Beneficial choices include carp, cod, monkfish, perch, sardine, salmon, snail, fava bean, black-eye pea, adzuki bean, lentil, soybean, peanut and peanut butter, artichoke, oat, rye, carrot, and collard greens. Neutral choices include jicama, chicken, grouse, bass, butterfish, mullet, pike, tilapia, farmer cheese, feta cheese, goat cheese, yogurt, egg, and almonds. Harmful choices include bacon, beef, buffalo, duck, mutton, veal, venison, lobster, cheese, whey, cashew, Brazil nut, wheat, mushroom, and olive."
      },
      {
        title: 'Blood group B stands apart because climate change shaped it',
        text: "Humans began on the flat, tropical savannah, but overhunting and overcrowding pushed them to look for new food sources. They started to move.\n\nThe cold, dry, mountainous parts of the Indian subcontinent and the empty plains of the Central Asian steppes were tough places. These conditions triggered the genetic changes that led to blood group B. This makes B unique, because it is the only group that came about this way.\n\nBlood group B grew and spread because of the harsh climates its early carriers faced.\n\nIt is fair to say that blood group B may have been the only group able to handle such a tough environment. The early carriers of this gene were often nomads. They depended on herding animals and dairy. We cannot say that everyone who lived this way was type B, but many of the strongest survivors likely were.\n\nBlood group B has the traits needed to thrive in hard settings, but it has its weak spots, like every other group. Evidence shows that this type is more likely to develop unusual, slow-moving viral and neurological problems, including ALS. Type B also runs a higher risk of cerebral aneurysm and asthma. There is no guarantee a person with type B will face these issues, but the risk is higher than for other groups.\n\nOn the positive side, this group sees less arthritis, less fibromyalgia, and lower rates of some cancers.\n\nHere are some harmful and beneficial foods for type B. Beneficial foods include goat, lamb, mutton, rabbit, venison, caviar, croaker, cod, mackerel, sardine, cottage cheese, goat cheese, milk, yogurt, kidney bean, lima bean, millet, oat, rice, beet, and carrot. Neutral foods include beef, buffalo, liver, pheasant, turkey, carp, herring, mullet, perch, butter, wheat, chicken egg, snap bean, soybean, almond, and barley. Harmful foods include bacon, chicken, duck, goose, veal, bass, crab, lobster, egg, lentil, wheat, olive, radish, and tomato."
      },
      {
        title: 'Why blood group AB stands out as the newest of the four',
        text: "We turn now to AB, the rarest of the four. Many researchers call AB the most recent blood group, and some even see it as a human creation. AB appeared when A and B carriers crossed paths, through migration or invasion, and their genes combined in their children.\n\nOne of AB's defining features is its wide tolerance. Because it carries both A and B antigens, it treats anything A-like or B-like as part of itself. The downside is that AB carriers run the highest cancer rate of any group. The bright side is that viruses often have a smaller effect on AB, perhaps because it formed later and in a different way from the older groups.\n\nEvery blood group has trade-offs, but the heaviest one for AB may be the higher risk of heart disease. That makes a thoughtful diet and regular exercise especially important for AB carriers. By choosing good foods and steering clear of the ones that tend to cause trouble, you give yourself a real chance at a longer, healthier life.\n\nAB carriers often handle allergies and autoimmune conditions better than other types.\n\nThe Hepatitis B virus antigen is often missing in AB blood, which leaves AB carriers more open to the harshest forms of that disease.\n\nAB brings together the strengths and weaknesses of A and B in one package.\n\nTo round out the picture, here are some foods that suit AB well and some that do not. These can help reduce risks and bring out the benefits of this rare type. Strong choices include turkey, cod, grouper, monkfish, pike, pickerel, salmon, sardine, snail, tuna, cottage cheese, milk, yogurt, lentil, walnut, millet, oat, and rye. Neutral choices include kelp, ginger, cucumber juice, carrot, agar, wheat, barley, flaxseed, cashew, Brazil nut, almond milk, and white beans. Foods to limit include beef, chicken, duck, buffalo, crab, haddock, oyster, shrimp, black-eye pea, kidney bean, lima bean, sorghum, and capers."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "The ABO blood group gives a useful structure for thinking about personal diets, and the results so far have been broad and positive. Still, even with Dr. Peter D'Adamo's passion for the work, the wider scientific community has been slow to accept the theory because the supporting evidence is thin.\n\nAs of 2013, a review of thousands of studies on blood type diets found that not a single one was well-built and accurate. Many studies do show that the suggested diets, like the type A diet rich in vegetables and fruit, are good for health. But the benefit was not limited to any blood group. Nearly anyone eating that way became healthier.\n\nSo, while there is nothing wrong with the diets themselves, there is no strong proof of a blood type link. Even without that link, one thing is sure to boost your immune system: a regular exercise habit. Pair that with a healthy diet and you have the foundation for a balanced life.\n\nThere is no single diet that fits everyone. You may be a certain blood group and find the matching list does not work well for you. Maybe you have a sensitivity that clashes with the suggestions. If so, keeping a food journal will help you spot which foods lift you up and which hold you back. From there, you can shape a plan that truly fits you.\n\nTry this. If you do not know your blood group, a quick visit to your doctor and a simple blood test will tell you. Different diets work for different people. A vegetarian plan might suit one person, while a meat-rich plan might suit another, so try a few foods and see what feels right. A food journal is a good way to track how your body reacts to different meals.\n\nDid you read it all the way through?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'eat-to-beat-disease.json': {
    base: { id: 'eat-to-beat-disease', title: 'Eat to Beat Disease', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781649929992 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Food as medicine',
        text: "Health is your body's constant work of fighting off invaders and repairing damage. And guess what powers this work? Food. As the old saying goes, you are what you eat. As we walk through this topic, a few things may surprise you.\n\nPicture walking into a giant pharmacy with aisles that seem to go on forever. Each shelf holds not pills but fruits, vegetables, grains, and spices. So every bite you take can work like medicine.\n\nEating can either build your health or make you feel unwell. Because of that, you have to pay attention to what you put on your plate. Every meal is a choice, whether you think about it or not, and that choice shapes how well your body's defenses work.\n\nYour body relies on five key systems to stay healthy. These include angiogenesis, regeneration, the microbiome, DNA protection, and immunity.\n\nThese systems work day and night to keep disease at bay. But they can only do their best work when you give them the right fuel.\n\nPlan your meals in advance so that on a busy day you do not end up snacking on chips.\n\nModern medicine now recognizes the power of food. Some of the top schools in the world are even adding cooking classes to their training. They know that medicine plays a role, but food does more than any pill to keep disease from taking hold. The good news is that you do not need a prescription to tap into this power. The choices sit right in front of you, and this knowledge can help you turn each meal into a strong shield against illness.\n\nBy the end of this summary, you will see how specific foods can boost each of your defense systems. Are you ready to step into the world of food and strengthen what your body already does well? Read on."
      },
      {
        title: 'The choice is yours',
        text: "It is easy to miss the deep link between what you eat and how you feel. But your plate holds more than just a way to fill your stomach. It is a doorway to whole-body health.\n\nThink about Mediterranean meals, with olives, nuts, and fresh produce at the center. It is not a coincidence that heart problems are less common in places where people eat this way. The patterns we see in food and health are not luck. They show the quiet magic of what we put in our bodies.\n\nSpeaking of magic, have you ever had a handful of blueberries? They are more than a sweet treat. They are loaded with antioxidants, especially flavonoids. These compounds are a gift from nature, and they help our brains. Eating them often can sharpen memory, turning a small berry into a brain booster.\n\nNow move from berries to spices. Picture turmeric and ginger, golden and warm. Beyond adding flavor to food, they have a long history as remedies. Turmeric, full of curcumin, helps calm inflammation, the root of many long-term illnesses. With a small sprinkle, you are giving your body armor against future trouble.\n\nPick products with care, leaning toward those that support your body.\n\nFurther down the aisle, you find the quiet champions: fiber-rich foods. Beans, lentils, and whole grains do more than fill space. They feed the trillions of microbes in your gut, which shape your mood, your immune system, and more. Every fiber-rich meal is a step toward a balanced inner world.\n\nBut while we celebrate certain foods, it is worth remembering that no single superfood does it all. Only a balanced diet, over time, brings real results. It is about steady commitment, not one good choice. So a green smoothie is great, but pairing it with fries waters down the effort.\n\nAll in all, your body craves rhythm and regularity. Good, thoughtful nutrition should become your way of life, not a passing phase. Treat food with respect, because it shapes your health more than almost anything else. Forget about short, painful diets. The golden rule is that healthy eating is a system for life."
      },
      {
        title: 'Your kitchen as a wellness hub',
        text: "The kitchen sits at the heart of many homes, once thought of as a place to throw together a meal. Today, it is a center of creativity, health, and change. Here, intentions turn into habits and small choices grow into lasting lifestyles.\n\nThe way your kitchen is set up quietly shapes what you eat. Picture a counter covered in candy jars next to a counter with a bright bowl of fresh fruit. The fruit, with its lively color, gently nudges you toward a healthier pick. Small shifts like this lay the groundwork for habits that last.\n\nTake a moment to think about your fridge. Most of us push vegetables to the back. Pulling them to the front, right where you can see them, can change everything. Spotting a fresh bell pepper or a crisp head of lettuce every time the door opens might inspire a heart-healthy salad or a quick stir-fry.\n\nBeyond what sits in the fridge, think about the tools in your drawers and on your walls. A blender in good hands can turn plain cashews into a creamy sauce. A sharp knife invites you to slice and dice, turning vegetables into colorful, tasty meals.\n\nYour pantry has changed too. White rice and canned goods now share shelf space with nutty quinoa, tiny chia seeds, and creamy almond butter. These additions are more than kitchen experiments. They show a growing awareness of health and wellness. Recall the small but meaningful swaps people make, from generic cooking oils to rich avocado oil, or from sugary sodas to crisp sparkling water.\n\nSwap sweets for natural marmalade, dark chocolate, and dried fruits.\n\nThe kitchen is more than appliances and ingredients. It reflects your values, your understanding of food, and your concern for the planet. Choosing produce from local farmers or cutting down on waste paints a bigger picture of mindful living.\n\nSo stepping into the kitchen today comes with a fresh outlook. It is no longer a routine chore but a chance to engage with a space full of possibility."
      },
      {
        title: 'More does not always mean better',
        text: "As you go deeper, you will see that it is not just what you eat but how much. The right amount matters as much as the food itself.\n\nFor example, the antioxidants in dark chocolate are good for the heart, but eating whole bars every day is not the way to go. Enjoying a small piece with care is the balance between health and pleasure. Red wine has resveratrol and other benefits, but it also shows why moderation matters. It is not about drinking more, but about appreciating each sip.\n\nUnderneath the surface sit nutrient stars like omega-3 fatty acids. Found in salmon and walnuts, they matter a lot for the brain. But loading your plate with salmon or piling on walnuts is not the answer. The key is regular, mindful inclusion: a salmon dish here, a sprinkle of walnuts there.\n\nDiversify your diet to give your body the full range of nutrients it needs.\n\nTread with awareness. Spinach is full of iron and calcium, but too much can cause trouble because of its oxalates. Brazil nuts are packed with selenium, which is a good reminder that there is a fine line between enough and too much.\n\nDo not skip personal checks and chats with your doctor. Bodies differ by age, activity level, and genes. A trained athlete's needs are not the same as someone with a quiet daily routine. When you understand and respect your body's uniqueness, you can tune your diet to fit you.\n\nA flood of nutrition advice can feel like being lost in a maze. But with knowledge and clear intention, the path appears. Each meal and each bite becomes a step toward balance, a meeting point of pleasure and nourishment. As you go on, the real heart of nutrition shows itself: harmony. The secrets of energy also live in this golden balance.\n\nA useful example: the Japanese follow the hara hachi bun me principle, which means eat until you are eighty percent full. It is a wise idea, because often you have had enough before you feel stuffed."
      },
      {
        title: 'Your diet does not have to be boring',
        text: "Now that you know the basic rules, here are some examples of a healthy, balanced day. In an ideal week, you would eat three meals a day on a steady schedule. You can also add a healthy snack. Let these ideas inspire you to plan meals that are as nourishing as they are tasty.\n\nMorning light streams through the window, marking the start of a new day. What better way to greet it than with a bright green smoothie? With fresh spinach, creamy avocado, a kick of ginger, and soothing almond milk, it gives you a burst of energy. For mornings that need something more, a warm bowl of oatmeal topped with berries, chia seeds, and a drizzle of honey offers both taste and nourishment.\n\nAs noon approaches, hunger settles in, and a quinoa salad gets its moment. This hearty grain, tossed with crisp cherry tomatoes, cool cucumber, and tangy feta, becomes a burst of flavor and texture. For something warm, a lentil soup spiced with cumin and turmeric whispers comfort and wellness.\n\nEvening arrives. Picture a plate of grilled salmon, its richness balanced by the gentle crunch of steamed asparagus and the nuttiness of quinoa pilaf. Vegetarians, do not worry. Bell peppers, generously stuffed with wild rice, beans, and a touch of cheese, make a picture of flavor and balanced nutrition.\n\nAdd spices to your dishes to bring exciting flavors to life.\n\nSnacking, often seen as a way to fill a gap, gets its time in the spotlight. Almonds and walnuts become trusty sidekicks, offering fullness and steady energy. For moments when you want something sweet, fruit paired with a nut butter dip is hard to beat.\n\nThe real magic is in the sheer range of choices out there. The world of ingredients is wide and varied, waiting for you to explore and play. The focus stays on whole, nutrient-rich foods that bring a balanced mix of proteins, fats, and carbohydrates. With that in mind, explore other cuisines to find new, unusual flavor pairings and make your food life richer.\n\nAround the world, palates are growing more curious as cultures blend and new foods cross borders, in the words of William W. Li."
      },
      {
        title: 'An unexpected benefit',
        text: "Some foods are especially good for your immune system. Keep them in mind and add them to your cart at the store.\n\nWhite button mushrooms are bursting with bioactives like beta-glucan, and they lead the pack in boosting immunity. Garlic sits beside them, prized for its flavor and its long history in folk medicine. Broccoli sprouts also pack a punch. They carry about one hundred times more sulforaphane, a compound that wakes up the immune system, than fully grown broccoli. A dash of heat from chili peppers does more than add fire. Their bright colors signal lutein, beta-carotene, and zeaxanthin, each with its own role in the body.\n\nOther foods stand out for where they come from. A few examples follow. Squash blossoms, those lovely yellow flowers at farmers' markets, are more than pretty. They hold spinasterol, a bioactive that fights cancer cells, supports immunity, and protects DNA. Persimmons, the fruit that looks a bit like a tomato, are loaded with extracts that have shown the power to fight several cancers. Wasabi, the real kind, the rhizome of a Japanese plant, is a strong force against breast, colon, and liver cancer cells. Bitter melon may not be everyone's favorite, but it is a powerhouse for fighting cancer, lowering cholesterol, and managing diabetes. Fiddleheads and truffles, from the coiled tips of young ferns to the earthy treats found beneath the forest floor, are full of bioactives that help the body in many ways.\n\nThere is also a finding that may surprise you. Beer. Before you raise an eyebrow, this is not a call to chug pints. Moderation is the key. But research shows that beer, especially the nonalcoholic kind, contains bioactives that are good for the heart.\n\nFollow the latest findings from nutritionists to rethink familiar products.\n\nThe beauty of these foods is in how they change our view, reminding us that science and nature often keep secrets waiting to be uncovered.\n\nFoods once dismissed as unhealthy or treated as guilty pleasures may actually have real benefits and deserve a second look, in the words of William W. Li."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Many countries focus their health systems on treating disease rather than preventing it. Instead of only responding to sickness after the fact, there is huge value in promoting good health from the start. One key idea to keep in mind is that food plays a major role in keeping us well.\n\nWhat we eat is more than satisfying hunger or enjoying a treat. It is about giving our bodies what they need to stay strong, heal, and renew. By understanding the benefits of certain foods, we build up our body's defenses for whatever comes our way.\n\nTaking charge of our health, mostly through food, is more than a personal choice. It is part of a larger movement to rethink what health means. Even though research and changes in care matter a great deal, the choices we make each day, like what we put on our plates, can make a real difference. When we choose to eat well, it helps not only us but the people around us.\n\nAs you step into the food world, remember that every bite can be a small adventure. Stay open to discovery and do not be afraid to question old ideas. Foods from around the world bring new flavors and also give us tools to defend and strengthen our health.\n\nSo the next time you are at a gathering, share these tips as fun facts and as a tribute to the wonder of nature and science.\n\nTry this. Add a Mediterranean-inspired meal to your week once. Swap your usual snacks for blueberries or nuts to give your brain a lift. Add turmeric to at least one dish every day. Practice moderation: enjoy treats like dark chocolate, but keep portions small. Refresh your kitchen: invest in good tools and stock your pantry with whole, nourishing ingredients.\n\nDid you read it all the way through?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'eat-to-live.json': {
    base: { id: 'eat-to-live', title: 'Eat to Live', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781650023460 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'The best diet for weight loss and lasting health',
        text: "Food is part of our everyday lives, so ordinary that we hardly think about it. Yet it carries many meanings, from pure energy to harmful cravings. Our relationship with food shapes how we feel about our bodies, giving us confidence or pulling it away. Whether the goal is weight loss or muscle gain, everyone is looking for the answer: what is the right way to eat?\n\nDr. Fuhrman offers his formula, building his approach on the nutritional value of food. The density of nutrients per calorie is the most important factor in his weight loss plan. He sums it up as Nutrients divided by Calories equals Health. The more nutrients you take in, the better your health.\n\nThe nutrient value of your food matters more than the calories you eat.\n\nProtein, fat, and carbohydrates give you calories. Nutrients come from other sources, like vitamins, fiber, and minerals. Eating foods rich in nutrients is the foundation of a healthy diet.\n\nMany people miss this simple truth about weight loss, so there is a real need for clear, mass education. The change you want depends on grasping these ideas. Once you understand the role of nutrients in losing weight, eating well becomes much easier.\n\nStart taking your health seriously now to prevent bigger problems later.\n\nEveryone wants a body free of disease. We are all looking for proven ways to stay well. Many people know that a better diet and more exercise can change them, but they lack the drive to act. This summary will lay the foundation you need to start building a healthier body, showing what is possible when you change how you eat."
      },
      {
        title: 'Junk food blocks good health and drives obesity',
        text: "Americans eat a lot of junk food. These foods are called junk because they offer very little nutrition. They are also the main reason obesity has grown in America, costing the health system about one hundred billion dollars a year. Most alarming, obesity doubles the death rate in the U.S.\n\nObesity is a serious health crisis in the U.S. and a growing problem worldwide.\n\nDoctors find it hard to treat obesity for several reasons. Both primary care doctors and specialists struggle to make real progress with patients who are obese, partly because junk food is everywhere and easy to get hooked on. Studies show that even patients who manage to lose weight at first often gain it back later.\n\nPeople with obesity may be drawn to quick fixes. They end up with risky surgeries or fad diets that only work for a short time. The problem is that people gain the weight back when they stop the diet. The results of any well-designed diet depend on sticking to its rules. People tend to drift, so they end up worse off than when they started.\n\nDrug companies have tried to create and sell pills to solve obesity, but those efforts have not done much. Most bodies react badly to these methods because they are short-term and do not lead to lasting change.\n\nIf you do not make real changes in what you eat, pills your doctor prescribes will not make you healthier or extend your life, in the words of Joel Fuhrman, MD.\n\nThe only real answer is to cut down or wipe out the disease-causing, addictive foods in our diet. Today, the evidence is strong: you can add years to your life by eating less and choosing better foods.\n\nA useful fact: a paper by Dr. Albert Stunkard and Mavis McLaren-Hume found that ninety-five percent of dieters return to junk food after reaching their weight loss goal. They end up regaining the weight and often adding more. Following a diet does not always change the way you think about food."
      },
      {
        title: 'Processed food pushes essential nutrients out of your diet',
        text: "Fruits are a key part of a healthy diet. Many studies have shown the protection they offer against serious illnesses like cancer.\n\nFruits are a great addition to your meals, helping fight aging and protecting the brain.\n\nRecent research shows that fruits like blueberries carry anthocyanins, which help slow aging. Some studies have also found that fruits can help prevent cancer and heart disease. Eating more of them is always a good idea, especially raw. So instead of drinking orange juice, try eating an orange. You will take in less sugar and gain more nutritional value.\n\nAt the same time, processed carbohydrates have far fewer micronutrients than fruits, including fiber, vitamins, and minerals. That loss is a direct result of processing, which strips out the good stuff.\n\nA study of sixty-five thousand women, followed for six years, showed that those who ate processed carbohydrates were two and a half times more likely to develop type II diabetes than those who ate high-fiber foods.\n\nOnce carbohydrates are processed, they lose touch with their natural nutrients. Your bloodstream soaks them up fast, and blood sugar jumps above normal. Your body goes into a stress state, and the pancreas pumps out insulin to keep up. Over time, your body needs even more insulin. As a result, body fat grows and the risk of diabetes climbs.\n\nTo lose weight, stay away from processed foods.\n\nRefined carbohydrates are a food group that affects your health directly, so it pays to be careful with them. You probably eat them often, in pasta, bread, and other flour-based foods. White rice is just as low in nutrition as pasta and white bread.\n\nThose foods turn into body fat quickly and can make you hungrier. The more you eat, the more you want. The ingredients that fuel obesity the most are the ones mixing butter, sugar, and flour."
      },
      {
        title: 'The hidden danger of animal protein',
        text: "There is a clear link between eating animal protein and heart disease. You can see it in the levels of plasma apolipoprotein B, a particle that, when high, raises the risk of heart disease. Eating lots of protein drives those levels up, while eating vegetables drives them down. On top of that, animal protein pushes cholesterol up, while vegetables help bring it down.\n\nThe link between animal protein and blood cholesterol is the reason people on low-fat diets often do not see a big drop in their cholesterol. To really lower cholesterol, people have to cut out most animal protein.\n\nEating lots of animal protein can also raise the risk of colon cancer.\n\nA study a few years ago looked at the eating habits of thirty-six thousand adults to learn how diet affects the growth of cancer cells. The participants were split into groups. One group was told to cut out red and white meat. The other group got no dietary advice. The group that cut out red and white meat had a lower rate of colon cancer.\n\nAny kind of meat can feed many health problems, so try to cut back or swap it for healthier options.\n\nFruits and vegetables are the foods most strongly linked to a long life. This is not just about being vegetarian. It is about eating fresh fruit and raw, leafy salads.\n\nMany Americans prefer to gamble with their health, hoping the drug industry will find a fix. A company that could lower cancer rates by eighty percent or more would be the richest in history, but no such company exists. So it is in your interest to use this life-extending gift, and eat your fruits and vegetables.\n\nStudies keep showing that more than any other food, fruit is linked to lower death rates from all cancers combined, in the words of Joel Fuhrman.\n\nWe pour billions into donations chasing a cure that does not exist yet. It is time to deal with the root cause of illness. That is the only way to win.\n\nA useful note: soy and beans are full of nutrients that fight and prevent cancer. They can also help protect against reproductive cancers, including breast and prostate cancer."
      },
      {
        title: 'High-carb foods keep calories low while you watch your fats',
        text: "Carbohydrates are the body's natural fuel. They power the daily work of the brain and muscles. That is why foods with unrefined carbohydrates are the most nourishing, giving you plenty of fiber and very few calories.\n\nFat has about five more calories per gram than protein or carbohydrates. Balance your diet by knowing the value of each macronutrient.\n\nYou can enjoy these carbs without worrying about a big calorie jump, because they are whole and unprocessed. Choose whole wheat products, brown rice, oatmeal, and quinoa, and bring them into your meals. The high fiber in unprocessed carbohydrates helps you feel full and satisfied.\n\nIt is the things we add to our carbs that make them feel fattening. Carbs on their own are not fattening. They are healthy. A cup of mashed potatoes has about one hundred and thirty calories, but a single tablespoon of butter pushes that to two hundred and thirty.\n\nMacronutrients like protein, fat, and carbohydrates matter as much as micronutrients like vitamins and minerals for a balanced diet.\n\nMeat, dairy, and oils are calorie-rich foods. But they are not the most filling, so we tend to eat a lot of them before we feel satisfied, which adds up to a lot of calories.\n\nYour body burns about twenty-three percent of the calories from carbohydrates to turn the glucose into fat. But food fat turns into body fat much faster. Your body can turn one hundred calories of food fat into about ninety-seven calories of body fat. Food fat is not processed or changed before the body stores it, which leads to weight gain.\n\nThat is why it pays to keep an eye on the fats you eat. You do not have to weigh every gram of every macronutrient, but it helps to know the nutritional value of the foods you eat often."
      },
      {
        title: 'Watch out for addiction: food toxins can be as harmful as drugs',
        text: "When your body gets used to a harmful substance, that is called addiction. You feel a rush when you use the substance. But if you stop, you feel sick as your body tries to repair the damage. This stage is called withdrawal.\n\nA good way to fight withdrawal is to distract the body. You can do that by eating more. Digesting food helps ease withdrawal symptoms.\n\nDuring withdrawal, people often lose their appetite because they are focused on the substance they are giving up. In those cases, the body uses stored glycogen for fuel. When those stores run low, true hunger sets in. If food does not arrive in time, the body starts gluconeogenesis, breaking down muscle to get glucose.\n\nWithdrawal symptoms from food look a lot like those from drugs.\n\nGlucose is not something your body makes. It comes from food. First, the body uses its stores of fat and amino acids from muscle. Breaking down muscle is not good for the body, so it is a last resort. Before that happens, the body sends signals called true hunger. If you do not answer those signals in time, gluconeogenesis kicks in.\n\nSignals from your throat, neck, and mouth signal true hunger. Signals from your stomach and head warn you about dehydration.\n\nTrue hunger is not as uncomfortable as it sounds. Food tastes better and eating feels better in this state. The body is ready to digest, and the right enzymes are in place. So there is less chance of overeating when you are truly hungry.\n\nToxic hunger, the kind that hits during withdrawal, is far less pleasant. It can bring headaches, fatigue, irritability, stomach cramps, and bloating. You can avoid it by eating the right amount of nutrient-rich food at the right times, and by paying attention to what you eat. After all, your diet is the key to a long, healthy, happy life."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "A healthy diet is not a complicated secret. It should not become an obsession either, but a way to feel good in your body almost without thinking. A basic grasp of macro and micronutrients, of what your food is worth, and of how your body handles it gives you what you need to stay well and avoid health crises.\n\nPay attention to your macro and micronutrients. First, keep a good balance of protein, fat, and carbohydrates. Second, cut back on heavily processed foods, so your body does not get used to pumping out too much insulin and storing extra fat. Third, get creative in the kitchen and enjoy the taste of natural, unprocessed food.\n\nOtherwise, you can end up with a food addiction that slowly harms your body.\n\nThe same goes for refined carbohydrates and large servings of meat. By eating less of them, you can keep your diet healthier and drop extra weight.\n\nAnother easy way to stay well is to use less salt. The average person eats up to five or ten times more sodium than is recommended, which raises blood pressure over the years. Even if your blood pressure is fine now, cutting back on salt lowers your future risk.\n\nRemember, eating well is not a chore. Get creative, explore your options, and aim for balance so you feel good in your body.\n\nTry this. Avoid eating or snacking when you are not truly hungry. Listen to your body and stop when your stomach feels full. Go for lighter dinners to make digestion easier. Cut back on salt and heavily processed foods, and let fruits and rich, whole meals fill that space instead.\n\nDid you read it all the way through?"
      }
    ]
  },
  'eating-animals.json': {
    base: { id: 'eating-animals', title: 'Eating Animals', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781650118460 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Grandma’s chicken and the author’s journey toward vegetarianism',
        text: "The author's relationship with food was shaped by his family, especially his grandmother. She cooked just one dish, chicken with carrots, yet as kids, Jonathan and his brother Frank thought she was the greatest cook in the world. She had survived World War II, and her view of food was nothing like ours today. Unhealthy products did not exist in her mind. She believed the rounder the kids, the healthier they were, and she even made sure they drank Coca-Cola. For her, food carried fear, faith, and love.\n\nThe way we see food is shaped by what we went through. For some, food is sacred. For others, it is easy to throw it away without a second thought.\n\nThere was a moment when the Foer brothers were eating dinner with their vegetarian babysitter. They asked why she would not eat the chicken. She said she did not want to hurt any living being. That was the moment the author realized a chicken could feel pain the way a person can. He became a vegetarian for a few years, but the resolve faded. He ended up pretending to be vegetarian at school while eating meat at home. In college, he kept eating meat because he loved the taste.\n\nWhen Foer met his future wife, they had one thing in common. They both kept slipping from vegetarianism back into eating meat. After the wedding, they promised each other they would be vegetarian, and again they failed. But when their son was born, Foer saw a chance to make a change, at least for this small new person. As we grow up, our parents pass on the rules of eating. We are told not to eat soup for breakfast, an odd rule, and we are told chicken is fine but parrots are out, which would surprise a hawk. These rules shape who we become more than we realize.\n\nReading Eating Animals will help you see your own eating habits and your family's food culture with new eyes. You will step into the world where animals live. The journey will be eye-opening, because some facts lay bare the shameful way we raise animals for food. You will probably feel pulled toward vegetarianism and toward helping animals in other ways, which is good, because they need our support now more than ever."
      },
      {
        title: 'Owning a pet shows that every animal has its own personality',
        text: "What about our attitudes toward animals? That, too, is passed from our parents to us and then to our children. Foer's grandmother and mother were afraid of dogs, and the author followed their lead. He panicked every time a dog ran at him in the park or in a friend's home. Naturally, he never imagined himself as someone who would adopt a dog. Then he saw George, the future puppy of his life, asleep on Seventh Avenue. At first, he could not bring himself to feed her from his hand. Soon, he was letting her lick his face. From that moment, he was a typical dog lover who melted at the sight of a wagging tail.\n\nAnyone who has a pet has likely noticed that animals are more than just needs and instincts, more than safety and food. Animals have personalities, which brings them closer to us. Foer saw that George had her own view of the world and even human-like feelings. Given his philosophical and practical leanings toward vegetarianism, the author understood clearly that he would never eat his dog or anyone else's. So why would he eat other animals? And why do people in some places, like parts of China and South Korea, not feel guilty about eating dogs for supposed health reasons?\n\nFood ethics are tangled, because food ties into taste buds and taste, personal stories, and social histories, in the words of Jonathan Safran Foer.\n\nEach country has its own culture that shapes what people eat. But we are also shaped by family, surroundings, social norms, and ethics. Sadly, ethics is rarely at the top of the list.\n\nMany well-known people changed their minds about meat and became vegetarian, like Kafka, the German-speaking writer. Shame was the word that captured his view of eating animals. Once, while visiting a Berlin aquarium, Kafka started talking to the fish. He said he could finally look at them without guilt, because he had stopped eating them.\n\nShame can push us toward more compassion.\n\nWhen people feel shame, they realize they traded away responsibility to someone or something for a passing pleasure. Shame does not let us forget something important. In Kafka's case, fish have been a symbol of forgetting, because people tend to think less about sea creatures than about farm animals when it comes to saving lives."
      },
      {
        title: 'What pushed the author to research how meat is produced',
        text: "Children and their direct questions wake up shame in parents by asking uncomfortable things. Adults have to find answers that will not confuse their kids or make them think their parents are bad. Children love to ask why. About meat, a child might ask, why do we eat chicken but not dogs? From a child's point of view, a chicken and a dog are not that different. They are living beings that feel pain and do not want to be eaten. How do we answer that without making ourselves look cruel? With that in mind, Foer decided to learn as much as he could, so he would not feel ashamed, and so he could raise a child who is more aware and more understanding.\n\nTo even begin explaining our culture of eating animals, the author had to draw a line between an animal and a person. It is hard to know what an animal feels, and we can only guess based on our own experience. Imagine you have a cat and you need to travel for a week. The cat has all the food and water it needs, but it is alone. Would it feel lonely? Would it suffer from your absence?\n\nTo treat animals better, we need to see them as people who look different from us.\n\nCruelty is the word that comes to mind when you dig into how our food reaches our plates. People invented the word bycatch to describe sea creatures trapped in fishing nets by chance. In reality, it is not an accident, because the nets are built and set in a way that pulls in far more sea life than the catch. To get one pound of trawled shrimp, twenty-six pounds of other sea creatures die. They get caught, they die, and they are tossed back into the sea. We do not even use that twenty-six pounds for food. So the author felt that when he sat down to a plate of five shrimp, he had to think about all the lives lost to bring him that small meal.\n\nA useful term: anthropodenial describes the habit of ignoring the deep similarities in experience between animals and humans."
      },
      {
        title: 'Sneaking into a farm and what it hides',
        text: "With an anonymous animal activist called C, Foer slipped into a turkey farm at night. At first glance, the birds looked content, warmed by the lights in their sheds. Then the author saw many dead turkeys lying near the living ones, full of scars, wounds, and signs of exhaustion. He watched C cut the throat of one dying turkey to end its pain. C had once worked in a poultry plant, doing the grim job of killing birds that the mechanical throat slitter had missed. She remembered the first time she saw the conditions the chickens lived in. The cages were too small for the birds to move, and they never got to step outside. That was when she knew that for those birds, death was a release from a life of suffering.\n\nIt all started with domestication, a shared evolution that helped humans and certain animals survive. Our ancestors did not force animals to become domestic. The wild was full of hardship, and it helped certain species to live with people, who offered care and safety in exchange for milk, eggs, and meat. At the time, animals had a good chance of living longer with humans than dying young in the wild. That bargain was fair, until modern times.\n\nAs farming grew and populations swelled, people saw a way to make more meat with less feed. For chickens, they bred bigger birds, the broilers. The bird's life shrank from years to about six weeks, which brought in more money for less cost. In 1946, people turned to genetics to shape the chickens we eat today. The birds grew sixty-five percent heavier, but they grew weaker, so farmers began to give them drugs to keep them alive.\n\nIn Foer's words, biodiversity gave way to genetic uniformity.\n\nIn the end, humans raised only two kinds of chickens: those bred for more meat and those bred for more eggs. The animals lost their individuality and became nothing more than food in the name of cheap production.\n\nRaising animals for food is a perfect example of a profit-first system that cares more about money than about the lives of the animals."
      },
      {
        title: 'The pandemic risk of factory farming',
        text: "Given how little care factory farms give the birds they raise, chicken health is far from great. The birds are often contaminated with bacteria like salmonella, or they are so weak that even a mild infection can take them down. Instead of fixing the conditions, farmers pump the birds full of drugs, especially antibiotics. You could understand that when a chicken is sick and needs help. But farmers give antibiotics to chickens that are not even sick yet, which is called nontherapeutic use.\n\nWhat is the harm in that, you might ask? Preventing disease sounds good, like taking vitamins and drinking warm tea to ward off a cold. But trying to prevent a bacterial or viral infection with drugs can actually make things worse. Have you heard about the rise of drug-resistant bacteria and viruses? When a sick person or animal takes a pill, most germs die. But a few stronger ones survive and learn new ways to resist the drug. Next time the same illness hits, the same medicine may not work. The hard part is that scientists cannot invent new antibiotics fast enough, leaving us exposed until they find new drugs that harm the germ without harming the person.\n\nEven if you do not take antibiotics when you are well, you can end up taking them through the meat of farmed animals. Millions of people now face the risk of a pandemic because germs keep mutating and becoming resistant to our drugs. For example, the H1N1 swine flu that spread in 2009 and 2010 started at a pig farm in North Carolina. Scientists who studied it were stunned to find that the strain had combined genes from pig, human, and bird viruses. That mix kept the pandemic going for an entire year, given how complex the germ was.\n\nTaking antibiotics to prevent a bacterial infection is a bad idea."
      },
      {
        title: 'More cruelty and a firm commitment to vegetarianism',
        text: "Raising cattle is also a cruel process. The cows are killed when they are only about a year old. In the past, farmers cared for their animals for four or five years. Temple Grandin, an American scientist, uncovered another grim truth about slaughterhouses. She found that one in four slaughterhouses did not kill every animal with a single blow. That means some cows suffered the pain until they finally died.\n\nFacts like these pushed Foer to commit fully to vegetarianism. He wanted his son to eat well, so he looked into whether a vegetarian diet is healthy. It turns out that vegetarianism can be just as healthy as a diet that includes meat. Once he no longer worried about nutrition, he could cut all ties with factory farms.\n\nBecoming a vegetarian to spare animals from cruelty may feel like too small a step. You might think that one person cannot change much by changing what they eat. Foer does not see it that way. You have more impact than you think. The American National Restaurant Association reported a rise in demand for vegetarian meals. They suggested that every food service spot add at least one vegetarian option. It turns out that a group of friends with even one vegetarian will often pick a place that serves vegetarian food.\n\nVegetarianism is about freedom of choice, and that ties into American history. The United States was once called the land of the free, partly because its people did not depend on Europe for food. Americans built their own farms and fed a large population. Today, we need the freedom to avoid certain foods.\n\nFood is not just a symbol of freedom, but the first requirement of freedom, in the words of Jonathan Safran Foer.\n\nThe diet choices parents make shape the food habits of the whole family. Teaching kids about food culture from an early age helps them make clear ethical choices later. The more people give up meat, the better chance we have of ending cruel factory farming.\n\nVegetarianism is not dangerous for health. But if you decide to go vegetarian, it is wise to talk to a doctor who can help you avoid meat in a safe and healthy way."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "Becoming a vegetarian is a hard path, because it means breaking a food culture built over centuries. Most likely, your family eats meat, and you grew up with turkey on Thanksgiving and veal at the cookout. In a way, switching to a meat-free life can feel like trying to quit smoking. Foer went back and forth between vegetarianism and meat, much like smokers who quit and then relapse many times. It is always better to try than to give up before you start. Eating Animals does not list the benefits of vegetarianism in a straight line. The author describes what the farming culture really looks like, and that alone is enough to make you at least consider plant-based food as a solid alternative to meat.\n\nIt is tough to accept how modern farmers treat birds and cattle. Knowing that this kind of cruelty sits so close to us shakes our faith in food ethics. But as Foer argues, you can do your part. With more restaurants and supermarkets offering vegetarian food, and more people going meat-free, we are clearly moving in the right direction. If this book moved you to try vegetarianism, do not be afraid of the hard parts of building new eating habits. Even if you simply cut back on the meat you usually eat, the animal world will thank you, because the more people step away from factory farming, the less chance it has to survive.\n\nTry this. Ask your family about their food habits and views on eating. This can teach you a lot about culture and the choices people make. Try adding more vegetarian meals to your week, like salads, nuts, fruits, and seeds, and watch how you feel. You may notice more energy from the vitamins in those foods. Visit an animal shelter and ask what they need. They often need food, hay, building materials, or financial support. Pick a way you can help and give our furry and feathered friends a hand."
      }
    ]
  },
  'economics-in-one-lesson.json': {
    base: { id: 'economics-in-one-lesson', title: 'Economics in One Lesson', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781617356485 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Economics lets you look past the present into the future that few can see',
        text: "Economics may be the most misunderstood field in the world. Even celebrated experts struggle with parts of it. The subject is always moving, and it stirs our selfish side more than almost anything else. It is easy to study physics, math, or art without getting tangled up in feelings. It is far harder to make economic policy without trying to grab some material benefit for yourself or the group you belong to.\n\nSelf-interest is part of the reason economic policy keeps shifting. If you look at the economic history of your country, you will see that different policies have come and gone, and most of them helped one group while hurting others.\n\nA good economic policy should not just help one group. It must serve the wider public.\n\nA key measure of a good policy is its long-term effect. You can tell a good economist from a bad one by how they look at a policy. A poor economist sees only the short-term gain. A good one weighs both the short and long term before deciding.\n\nComplex as it may seem, economics can be boiled down to a single lesson, and that is the point of this chapter. To put it simply, when you make economic policy, do not only look at the immediate gains. Look at the long-term effects. If those effects are positive, check that they help all groups, not just one.\n\nA useful note: many classical economists made the mistake of focusing only on the long term, and that led to serious problems. Economic policy should work well in both the short and the long run."
      },
      {
        title: 'Economic need only equals demand when there is real buying power',
        text: "Have you heard of the broken glass fallacy? It was first laid out in 1850 by economist Frédéric Bastiat in his essay Ce qu'on voit et ce qu'on ne voit pas, or That Which We See and That Which We Do Not See.\n\nHe used the essay to show that money spent to recover from damage does not add new value to a society. His broken glass parable was popular through the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. Many versions exist, but the lesson is the same. Picture a boy who throws a stone by accident and breaks a shopkeeper's window. The shopkeeper forgives him, but the window is still broken. That is a loss, because the shopkeeper did not plan for it. The glazier, though, gains, because he profits from the repair. The real question is this: is the broken window a good thing just because someone benefits?\n\nMany people, some economists included, treat it as a boost to the economy, since the glazier gets a new customer. But it is not. It is a loss, because the shopkeeper is spending money he had set aside for something else. Imagine the repair costs two hundred dollars, and he had planned to use that money for groceries. He would have had a whole shop and a stocked kitchen, but now he cannot. He has to give up on stocking his kitchen to fix his shop, so it is a clear loss.\n\nThe shopkeeper's need for repair went up, but his buying power did not.\n\nDemand only helps the economy when there is real money to back it up.\n\nWhen damage happens on a large scale, as in wars or terrorist attacks, or when prices rise and people must spend more, it is often mistaken for a boost to the economy. That is not true. Damage and rising prices create need, but people have to drop other needs to meet the more urgent ones, and that is a loss.\n\nContrary to a common belief, profit comes not from raising prices, but from finding efficiencies that lower the cost of production, in the words of Henry Hazlitt."
      },
      {
        title: 'It is not wise to spend public money unevenly just to create jobs',
        text: "The government pays for public projects mostly from taxes, the national reserve, and borrowed money, but mostly from taxes. Most people are happy to pay tax because the government promises to use the money to build better communities and create jobs. The government usually delivers, but there is a common economic trap. It is the illusion of creating jobs. Public money should not be used only to create jobs. It is fine if a project is something the public needs and jobs follow as a result, but when the goal is only to create jobs, leaders often end up funding projects that nobody really needs, and the spending goes to waste.\n\nThat also gives officials a chance to loot public funds. When the goal is to fund projects that benefit people, it is easier to keep track of the money.\n\nThe best way for the government to create jobs is not to fund more projects, but to offer tax breaks that encourage private businesses to grow and hire.\n\nIt is critical to remember the most important rule of economics when funding projects. The projects must benefit the whole society, not just a chosen few.\n\nHere is another reason to avoid using public funds to chase jobs. The harder the government pushes to create jobs, the more it has to tax its citizens. That raises the share of personal and corporate income taken in tax. People and companies become less willing to start new ventures, because of the high tax load. In the end, fewer private-sector jobs appear, and the government's goal of more jobs falls short."
      },
      {
        title: 'Private loans are healthier for the economy than government loans',
        text: "Loans are given to businesses and individuals to help them grow and to add to the national economy. Both private and public lenders offer loans, but they work in different ways. Private lenders know they do not have endless income, so they are very careful about who they lend to and how. Walk into a bank to ask for a loan and you will see just how strict they are. They want to vet you fully before handing over their money. They cannot afford to take wild risks.\n\nThe picture is different with the government. For some reason, economic advisers have convinced the government that it is fine to spend taxpayer money giving loans to people the private sector would not touch. Take farm loans. It is hard to imagine a bank lending to a farmer who has not shown that he can pay it back on time. But the government creates programs that let farmers borrow without proper vetting, with no clear proof they can repay.\n\nAs Willi Way puts it, borrow a little and if you cannot pay it back, it is your problem. Borrow a lot and if you cannot pay it back, it is the lender's problem.\n\nThe government often treats lending to citizens as an act of charity, and that hurts the economy. Lending money to someone you are not sure can repay is an economic mistake. The government does not hand money to just anyone, but many of the people who get government loans have not been properly checked. That mistake needs fixing, because it does more harm than good in any country that practices it.\n\nOn the issue of issuing loans and getting the money back, governments have a lot to learn from private lenders. A great deal of public money is never repaid."
      },
      {
        title: 'Are you afraid that AI and robots will take your job? Do not be',
        text: "You may have heard from the media, a friend, or a coach that AI is coming for your job. Many people around the world are on edge, because they have seen how technology has cost someone they know their job. Maybe you have lost a job yourself, because your employer swapped machines for hundreds or thousands of workers.\n\nIt is real. Technology has been taking jobs since the industrial age, and it is picking up speed as the world builds smarter machines. But there is the other side, the side most people miss. Technology does not just make jobs vanish. It also creates new industries with new kinds of work.\n\nFear will not stop machines from coming for your job, but adapting and learning new skills quickly will keep you valuable in the market.\n\nMachines may shake up the workforce in the short run, but history keeps showing that within a few years, more jobs appear than were lost. The pattern is interesting in hindsight. Here is how it plays out. A maker adopts a new machine that can do the work of half his staff and produce high quality at half the cost. He lays off the half he no longer needs. He earns more profit, because he can produce more goods for less. He pulls ahead of competitors still stuck in the old way. That does not last long, though, because they soon adopt the same technology. Once everyone does, the cost of production falls, the company that built the machine hires more workers to make more machines, and prices start to drop. In time, profits shrink as competition grows, and products or services become cheaper for buyers.\n\nThat is the full cycle. People do lose jobs in the early years of a new technology, but they can also reinvent themselves and pick up the skills the market now needs."
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: "In the industrial age, trade unions rose because industries believed that was the only way to keep their jobs safe. Their job was to lock down each trade and make sure members did not lose work to other trades. A carpenter was not allowed to do the painter's work, even when he could. An electrician was not allowed to do the plumber's work, and so on. All of this came from fear of losing work. Yet, the rise of trade unions had a downside for the economy. Consumers felt it the most. You had to hire two or three different pros to do a job that one person could have done without the trade rules. Trade unions still exist, and they are not all bad, but their actions need to be watched by economists and government officials to make sure they do not harm the economy of the country in the long run.\n\nTrade unions should not be torn down, because they give workers security and push for better conditions. But the government can step in, monitor their actions, and stop anything that hurts the national economy.\n\nTry this. Before backing any economic policy, make sure it does not help only one group and does not create long-term harm for everyone else.\n\nDid you read it all the way through?"
      }
    ]
  }
};
